article.headline: Dartmouth 21, Penn 13
article.story: HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- Tom Bennewitz threw two touchdown passes Saturday and set up another with a clutch throw while Dartmouth's defense held off Penn in a wild finish en route to a 21-13 victory in the Ivy League season opener for each team. The Quakers (0-3, 0-1 Ivy) made it close after partially blocking a punt with under three minutes remaining. Penn recovered at the Dartmouth 26 and three plays later Bryan Walker tossed 9 yards to Braden Lepisto for a touchdown, making it 21-12. Andrew Samson, who had field goals of 23 and 45 yards, kicked the extra point. Penn then recovered their kickoff at their 40. A pass interference play helped Penn move to the Dartmouth 6 where a fourth-down pass went incomplete with 22 seconds left to preserve the win for Dartmouth (1-2, 1-0). Dartmouth got its first touchdown late in the opening period. Bennewitz hit Eric Paul on a 19-yard pass to the Penn 1, then Hudson Smythe bulled into the end zone with 1:34 left. Andrew Kempler kicked the first of three extra points. In the third period, Brian Evans made a leaping end zone catch while closely defended to complete a 30-yard scoring play from Bennewitz. On the opening play of the final period, Bennewitz and Paul connected on a 29-yard TD pass play that put the game out of reach.
